recordings.loc: Breede River DC, Cape Winelands, Western Cape
recordings.rmk:
Pair calling at dusk from roof, trees and *Agave* peduncles, one on either side of me.  Full moon night though the moon was not yet up.  Both Barns and Spotted Eagle Owls along with Fierynecked Nightjars call most enthusiastically for the five days around full moon.  Habitat is farm 'garden' in succulent karoo.

This recording is highly filtered to try and hear the owls above the deafening crickets.  I will upload an unmodified recording as well.
At least two juveniles begging, while sitting on a roof; one of the adults arrives at 1:35 (same family as XC320775). Evening call for prayer in the background.
3 begging young (1 in foreground, sitting on a roof) and what is probably an adult calling in flight. Same birds as XC320775.
3 begging young (1 in foreground, sitting on a roof) and what is probably an adult calling in flight. Same birds as XC320776.
Single  bird calling twice (start of recording and 2:57) while flying overhead, probably hunting. At dusk two birds were seen chasing one another here.
Two adults (probably a pair) calling in flight, while two or three juveniles can be heard begging for food

There was old abandoned farmhouse where I knew a Barn Owl often roosts. Played a call and two birds answered.

ID Certainty 80%; based on XC154981 and XC353109.

Video recording made on Canon Powershot G3X camera (no visuals since at night); played back on computer, and re-recorded on Fujifilm X-S1 camera (Voice Memo facility) to get just soundtrack.  WAV file converted to MP3 using Audacity 2.1.2 (using default settings).

Habitat:  Namaqualand Klipkoppe Shrubland

Bird Position:  Not seen but probably on ground (very few trees here, few telephone poles)

Interactions:  Multiple similar calls from various positions (almost certainly multiple birds)
Considered by some as a seperate species: 'Sao Tomé Barn Owl' - endemic to Sao Tomé.
